  "summary": "two overworld portals are connected to the same nether portal",
  "environment_raw": null,
  "description": "i linked a nether portal in the overworld near my house to the nether but when tried to go back it sent me 300 blocks away from my house in an underground cave in the deepslate level n n",
  "Steps to Reproduce": "1. Create a new Survival world with default settings.\n2. Gather at least 10 Obsidian blocks and a Flint and Steel to construct a Nether portal.\n3. Build the first Nether portal in the Nether at coordinates X, Y, Z.\n4. Note the coordinates of the first Nether portal.\n5. In the Overworld, build two separate Overworld portals at approximately the same X and Z coordinates, but at different Y levels (for example, one at Y=64 and another at Y=160).\n6. Light both Overworld portals using Flint and Steel.\n7. Enter the first Overworld portal to travel to the Nether.\n8. From the Nether, travel to the coordinates of the first Nether portal and enter it to return to the Overworld.\n9. After returning, enter the second Overworld portal to test its linkage to the same Nether portal.\n10. Observe the location where you re-enter the Overworld and note if you are sent to a location significantly distant (e.g., 300 blocks away) from the second Overworld portal, such as in an underground cave at the deepslate level.",
  "Environment": "Minecraft Java Edition Version 25w32a (snapshot)",
  "Observed Behavior": "it sent me 300 blocks away from my house in an underground cave in the deepslate level.",
  "Expected Behavior": "I linked a nether portal in the overworld near my house to the nether but when tried to go back.",
